  <div class="container">
    <div class="content-sidebar-grid">

      <!-- MAIN COLUMN -->
      <main class="main-col">

        <!-- What is a conditional green card -->
        <section id="what-is" class="content-section">
          <h2>What Is a Conditional Green Card?</h2>
          <p>A <strong>conditional green card</strong> is a Lawful Permanent Resident (LPR) card issued when a foreign national receives a green card through marriage to a U.S. citizen and the marriage was less than 2 years old at the time of approval. It looks almost identical to a standard green card and grants the same core rights — but it expires after just 2 years and carries a requirement to prove the marriage is genuine before those 2 years are up.</p>
          <p>The formal immigration term is <em>conditional permanent residence</em>. On the card itself, you'll see the category printed as <strong>CR-1</strong> (if you entered as a spousal immigrant) or <strong>CR-6</strong> (if you were an immediate relative who adjusted status inside the U.S. after entering on a K-1 visa). Both mean the same thing: conditional, 2-year card.</p>

          <div class="alert-box alert-teal">
            <div class="alert-icon">&#128273;</div>
            <div>
              <strong>It is a real green card — just time-limited</strong>
              <p>A common fear is that a conditional green card is somehow "less than" a permanent green card. It isn't. The rights are the same. The only differences are the 2-year expiry and the requirement to file <SmartLink href="/i-751-petition-remove-conditions">Form I-751</SmartLink> to remove the conditions. You can work, travel, and live in the U.S. fully during the conditional period.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3>Why does USCIS issue a conditional card?</h3>
          <p>Congress created conditional permanent residence in 1986 specifically to deter marriage fraud — the practice of entering a sham marriage solely to obtain immigration benefits. The logic: if USCIS approves a green card for someone who has only been married a few months, there's no track record yet to verify the marriage is genuine. The 2-year conditional period gives the couple time to build that track record, then demonstrate it when they file I-751.</p>
          <p>By the time you file I-751, USCIS expects to see 2 years of documented shared life: joint finances, shared housing, family, photos, community ties. If the marriage was real, this evidence exists naturally. If it was fraudulent, it typically doesn't.</p>

          <h3>How it fits into the two paths to a marriage-based green card</h3>
          <p>Both major paths to a marriage-based green card can result in a conditional card — it all depends on how long the marriage is at the time of approval, not which path was taken:</p>

          <div class="paths-table-wrap">
            <table class="paths-table">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Path</th>
                  <th>Marriage &lt; 2 years at approval</th>
                  <th>Marriage 2+ years at approval</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><SmartLink href="/cr1-visa">CR-1 Spousal Visa</SmartLink> (abroad → U.S.)</td>
                  <td class="cell-highlight">Conditional green card (CR-1)</td>
                  <td class="cell-blue">Permanent green card (IR-1)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><SmartLink href="/k1-visa">K-1 Fiancé Visa</SmartLink> + <SmartLink href="/adjustment-of-status">Adjustment of Status</SmartLink></td>
                  <td class="cell-highlight">Conditional green card (CR-6)</td>
                  <td class="cell-blue">Permanent green card (IF-6)</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <div class="alert-box alert-info">
            <div class="alert-icon">&#128161;</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Tip: Couples who marry early in the K-1 process often end up conditional</strong>
              <p>Because the K-1 + Adjustment of Status process takes 18–30+ months from petition to green card, many K-1 couples who married shortly after the fiancé entered the U.S. will have been married less than 2 years when the I-485 is approved — resulting in a conditional card. This is very common and nothing to worry about.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Who gets conditional vs permanent -->
        <section id="who-gets" class="content-section">
          <h2>Who Gets a Conditional vs. Permanent Green Card?</h2>
          <p>The deciding factor is simple: <strong>how long the couple has been married at the moment USCIS (or the consular officer) approves the green card</strong>. USCIS looks at the approval date — not the petition filing date, not the interview date.</p>

          <div class="who-grid">
            <div class="who-card who-conditional">
              <div class="who-icon">&#9201;</div>
              <h3>You receive a CONDITIONAL (2-year) card if:</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Your marriage is less than 2 years old on the day USCIS or the consular officer approves your green card</li>
                <li>Category code on the card: CR-1 (entered as immigrant spouse) or CR-6 (adjusted status after K-1)</li>
                <li>You must file Form I-751 between months 21–24 to remove conditions</li>
                <li>Common for K-1 + AOS couples and couples who recently married before the CR-1 was filed</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="who-card who-permanent">
              <div class="who-icon">&#9989;</div>
              <h3>You receive a PERMANENT (10-year) card if:</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Your marriage is 2 years or older on the day of approval</li>
                <li>Category code on the card: IR-1 (entered as immigrant spouse) or IF-6 (adjusted status)</li>
                <li>No I-751 required — you skip the remove-conditions step entirely</li>
                <li>Common for couples who were married for several years before beginning the process, or whose CR-1 approval happened to fall just after their 2-year anniversary</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="alert-box alert-warning">
            <div class="alert-icon">&#128270;</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Check the category on your card right now</strong>
              <p>Look at the front of your green card. Find the field labeled "Category." If it reads CR-1, CR-2, CR-6, or CR-7 — you have a conditional card and must file I-751. If it reads IR-1, IR-2, IF-6, or similar IR codes — you have a permanent card and no I-751 is needed. If you are unsure, consult an immigration attorney before assuming you don't need to file.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Rights and restrictions -->
        <section id="rights" class="content-section">
          <h2>What Can You Do With a Conditional Green Card?</h2>
          <p>Many conditional green card holders are surprised to learn just how much the card allows. Because it is a true Lawful Permanent Resident card, almost everything a 10-year green card holder can do, a conditional green card holder can do too.</p>

          <div class="rights-grid">
            <div class="rights-card rights-yes">
              <div class="rights-card-header">
                <div class="rights-card-icon">&#9989;</div>
                <div class="rights-card-title">You CAN do all of this</div>
              </div>
              <ul class="rights-list yes-list">
                <li><strong>Work anywhere in the U.S.</strong> — No employer sponsorship needed. You have unrestricted work authorization.</li>
                <li><strong>Travel internationally</strong> — You can leave and re-enter the U.S. as a returning resident. Trips of less than 6 months generally do not affect your status.</li>
                <li><strong>Re-enter the U.S.</strong> — Your conditional green card serves as a valid travel document for re-entry.</li>
                <li><strong>Live anywhere in the U.S.</strong> — No restrictions on where you reside within the country.</li>
                <li><strong>Sponsor family members</strong> — You can petition for certain family members (though wait times for LPR family petitions are long).</li>
                <li><strong>Apply for a U.S. driver's license</strong> — In virtually all states, conditional green cards are accepted for license applications.</li>
                <li><strong>Open bank accounts, credit cards, mortgages</strong> — Full access to U.S. financial system.</li>
                <li><strong>Apply to most government and private jobs</strong> — Jobs requiring U.S. citizenship are the exception.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="rights-card rights-no">
              <div class="rights-card-header">
                <div class="rights-card-icon">&#10060;</div>
                <div class="rights-card-title">You CANNOT do these things</div>
              </div>
              <ul class="rights-list no-list">
                <li><strong>Vote in federal or state elections</strong> — Only U.S. citizens may vote. Voting as a non-citizen is a serious crime that can result in deportation and a permanent bar from citizenship.</li>
                <li><strong>Apply for U.S. citizenship yet</strong> — You must first remove conditions and hold permanent resident status for the required period (3 years as spouse of U.S. citizen).</li>
                <li><strong>Abandon LPR status without consequences</strong> — Extended absences (generally 6+ months) can trigger questions about whether you abandoned your U.S. residence.</li>
                <li><strong>Take certain security-clearance jobs</strong> — Some federal positions require U.S. citizenship specifically.</li>
                <li><strong>Let the card expire without filing I-751</strong> — Failing to file I-751 in time can result in loss of status and removal proceedings.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="alert-box alert-teal">
            <div class="alert-icon">&#9992;</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Traveling while I-751 is pending</strong>
              <p>Once you have filed I-751 and received your receipt notice (Form I-797), you can travel internationally and re-enter using your expired conditional green card plus the I-797 receipt notice together. Bring both documents every time you travel while your I-751 is pending. If you receive an updated extension notice, bring that as well.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- I-751 filing window -->
        <section id="filing-window" class="content-section">
          <h2>The I-751 Filing Window — The Most Critical Date in Your Conditional Period</h2>
          <p>The single most important thing to know about your conditional green card is this: you have a <strong>90-day window</strong> to file Form I-751, and filing outside it — either too early or too late — causes serious problems.</p>

          <div class="window-timeline">
            <div class="wt-track">
              <div class="wt-seg wt-wait">
                <div class="wt-seg-label">Wait period</div>
                <div class="wt-seg-sub">Do NOT file yet</div>
              </div>
              <div class="wt-seg wt-window">
                <div class="wt-seg-label">Filing window</div>
                <div class="wt-seg-sub">90-day window</div>
              </div>
              <div class="wt-seg wt-expired">
                <div class="wt-seg-label">Card expired</div>
                <div class="wt-seg-sub">Late filing risk</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="wt-labels">
              <div class="wt-label-item">Month 0 → Month 21 (21 months)</div>
              <div class="wt-label-item">Months 21–24</div>
              <div class="wt-label-item">Month 24+</div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>The window opens exactly <strong>21 months after your conditional green card was issued</strong> — which is the same as 90 days before the card's expiration date. The window closes on the card's expiration date itself. You can calculate your exact window by looking at the expiration date printed on your card and counting back 90 days.</p>

          <div class="window-cards">
            <div class="wc-card wc-green">
              <h3>&#9989; On-time filing (months 21–24)</h3>
              <p>USCIS accepts your petition, sends a receipt notice (I-797), and automatically extends your conditional residence for <strong>24 months</strong> while the case is pending. You remain fully authorized to live and work in the U.S. Keep your receipt notice with your passport at all times.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="wc-card wc-yellow">
              <h3>&#9888; Too early (before month 21)</h3>
              <p>USCIS will reject the petition and return your filing fee. Nothing serious — but you've lost time and postage. Refile when the 90-day window opens. Set a calendar reminder for day 1 of month 21 (your card's expiry minus 90 days).</p>
            </div>
            <div class="wc-card wc-red">
              <h3>&#128683; Too late (after month 24)</h3>
              <p>USCIS may still accept a late filing if you include a written explanation with credible good cause (serious illness, hospitalization, natural disaster, etc.). Without a strong explanation, you risk loss of LPR status and placement in removal proceedings. File immediately — do not delay further.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="alert-box alert-warning">
            <div class="alert-icon">&#128197;</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Example: How to calculate your window</strong>
              <p>Your conditional green card expires on October 10, 2026. Count back 90 days: your filing window opens on July 12, 2026. You may file any time between July 12 and October 10, 2026. Do not file before July 12 — USCIS will reject it. Do not file after October 10 without a late-filing explanation.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3>What happens immediately after you file</h3>
          <p>Within 2–6 weeks of USCIS receiving your I-751, you'll get a <strong>Form I-797 receipt notice</strong> in the mail. This notice serves several critical functions:</p>
          <ul style="list-style:none; display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:6px; margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; padding:0;">
            <li style="font-size:0.875rem; color:var(--color-muted); padding-left:1.25rem; position:relative; line-height:1.6;">
              <span style="position:absolute; left:0; color:#0d9488; font-weight:700;">&#10003;</span>
              It automatically extends your conditional permanent residence for <strong>24 months</strong> beyond your card's expiration date.
            </li>
            <li style="font-size:0.875rem; color:var(--color-muted); padding-left:1.25rem; position:relative; line-height:1.6;">
              <span style="position:absolute; left:0; color:#0d9488; font-weight:700;">&#10003;</span>
              It serves as proof of your continued work authorization — you can show it to employers who need to reverify your employment eligibility.
            </li>
            <li style="font-size:0.875rem; color:var(--color-muted); padding-left:1.25rem; position:relative; line-height:1.6;">
              <span style="position:absolute; left:0; color:#0d9488; font-weight:700;">&#10003;</span>
              Combined with your expired conditional green card, it serves as a re-entry document for international travel.
            </li>
            <li style="font-size:0.875rem; color:var(--color-muted); padding-left:1.25rem; position:relative; line-height:1.6;">
              <span style="position:absolute; left:0; color:#0d9488; font-weight:700;">&#10003;</span>
              It is the document that proves your case is pending if anyone asks about your immigration status.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- Missing the window -->
        <section id="missed-window" class="content-section">
          <h2>What Happens If You Miss the I-751 Filing Window?</h2>
          <p>Missing the I-751 window is serious, but it is not always the end of the road. USCIS has discretion to accept late-filed I-751 petitions when the petitioner can show good cause for the delay. Here's how to handle it:</p>

          <div class="alert-box alert-danger">
            <div class="alert-icon">&#128679;</div>
            <div>
              <strong>If you have missed the window: file immediately</strong>
              <p>Do not wait any longer. Every additional day increases your risk. Once your conditional green card expires without a pending I-751, you technically have no lawful immigration status in the U.S. File as soon as possible, include a thorough written explanation, and strongly consider consulting an immigration attorney before filing.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3>What "good cause" means for a late filing</h3>
          <p>USCIS does not define "good cause" with a strict list, but examples that have been accepted include:</p>
          <ul style="list-style:none; display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:6px; margin: 0.75rem 0; padding:0;">
            <li style="font-size:0.875rem; color:var(--color-muted); padding-left:1.25rem; position:relative; line-height:1.6;"><span style="position:absolute; left:0; color:#0d9488; font-weight:700;">&#10003;</span> Serious illness or hospitalization of the conditional resident or a close family member</li>
            <li style="font-size:0.875rem; color:var(--color-muted); padding-left:1.25rem; position:relative; line-height:1.6;"><span style="position:absolute; left:0; color:#0d9488; font-weight:700;">&#10003;</span> Death of an immediate family member causing extreme stress or disruption</li>
            <li style="font-size:0.875rem; color:var(--color-muted); padding-left:1.25rem; position:relative; line-height:1.6;"><span style="position:absolute; left:0; color:#0d9488; font-weight:700;">&#10003;</span> Natural disaster, fire, or other catastrophic event affecting the petitioner's ability to file</li>
            <li style="font-size:0.875rem; color:var(--color-muted); padding-left:1.25rem; position:relative; line-height:1.6;"><span style="position:absolute; left:0; color:#0d9488; font-weight:700;">&#10003;</span> Attorney error where the petitioner relied in good faith on incorrect advice and took reasonable steps to remediate</li>
            <li style="font-size:0.875rem; color:var(--color-muted); padding-left:1.25rem; position:relative; line-height:1.6;"><span style="position:absolute; left:0; color:#0d9488; font-weight:700;">&#10003;</span> Delays caused by circumstances outside the petitioner's control with documented evidence</li>
          </ul>
          <p>"I forgot" or "I didn't know" are generally <em>not</em> accepted as good cause on their own, though lack of awareness combined with prompt filing and a genuine marriage can sometimes work in your favor. A written explanation must accompany every late filing — USCIS will not waive the requirement simply because you file late.</p>
        </section>

        <!-- Joint vs waiver -->
        <section id="joint-vs-waiver" class="content-section">
          <h2>Joint Filing vs. Waiver — Who Can File What?</h2>
          <p>Form I-751 can be filed as a <strong>joint petition</strong> (with your spouse) or as a <strong>waiver petition</strong> (without your spouse's signature). Which applies to you depends entirely on your circumstances.</p>

          <div class="filing-type-grid">
            <div class="ft-card ft-joint">
              <div class="ft-badge">Most Common</div>
              <h3>&#129309; Joint Petition</h3>
              <p>Filed together with your U.S. citizen spouse. Both spouses sign Part 5 of Form I-751. This is the standard path for couples who are still married and in a genuine marital relationship.</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Both spouses sign the form</li>
                <li>Evidence of shared married life required</li>
                <li>Interview may or may not be required</li>
                <li>Typical denial rate is low with strong evidence</li>
                <li>Separation during I-751 processing does not automatically invalidate — the marriage must still be legally intact when filing</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="ft-card ft-waiver">
              <div class="ft-badge ft-badge-gray">Waiver Basis</div>
              <h3>&#128196; Waiver — File Without Spouse</h3>
              <p>You may file I-751 alone — without your spouse's signature — if one of the following legally recognized grounds applies:</p>
              <div class="waiver-reasons">
                <div class="wr-item">
                  <div class="wr-icon">&#128148;</div>
                  <div>
                    <strong>Divorce or annulment</strong>
                    <p>Marriage legally ended. Include the final decree. You may file while divorce is still pending and submit the decree when issued (include a cover letter explaining).</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="wr-item">
                  <div class="wr-icon">&#128149;</div>
                  <div>
                    <strong>Death of the U.S. citizen spouse</strong>
                    <p>Include the death certificate and evidence that the marriage was bona fide. You can still qualify for a waiver even without the joint filing partner.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="wr-item">
                  <div class="wr-icon">&#128737;</div>
                  <div>
                    <strong>Battery or extreme cruelty (VAWA)</strong>
                    <p>You or your child were subjected to battery or extreme cruelty by the U.S. citizen spouse. Police reports, protective orders, medical records, and counselor statements are all valuable evidence.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="wr-item">
                  <div class="wr-icon">&#9878;</div>
                  <div>
                    <strong>Extreme hardship</strong>
                    <p>Removal from the U.S. would cause extreme hardship to you or your children. This is a high evidentiary bar requiring detailed documentation of hardship factors.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="alert-box alert-warning">
            <div class="alert-icon">&#9878;</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Waiver cases are significantly more complex</strong>
              <p>Waiver-based I-751 petitions are held to a higher evidentiary standard, are more likely to require an interview, and have higher denial rates than joint petitions. If you are filing on any waiver basis — particularly divorce or cruelty — an immigration attorney is strongly recommended. The stakes are too high to navigate alone.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Evidence -->
        <section id="evidence" class="content-section">
          <h2>Evidence for Form I-751 — Proving Your Marriage Is Real</h2>
          <p>The core question USCIS is asking when it reviews your I-751 is the same question it has asked at every prior stage of the process: <em>is this a genuine marriage entered in good faith?</em> The difference now is that you have up to 2 years of married life to document. USCIS wants to see evidence that spans the entire conditional period — not just recent documents.</p>
          <p>Organize your evidence into labeled exhibits (Exhibit A, Exhibit B, etc.) with a cover sheet listing each exhibit. Include a brief explanation of what each document shows. The goal is to make the officer's job easy — a well-organized package signals a confident, legitimate petition.</p>

          <div class="evidence-cats">
            <div class="ev-cat ev-cat-top">
              <div class="ev-cat-header">
                <div class="ev-cat-icon">&#127970;</div>
                <h3>Financial Evidence <span class="ev-strength-badge badge-strong">Strongest</span></h3>
              </div>
              <div class="ev-items-list">
                <div class="ev-row">
                  <div class="ev-check">&#10003;</div>
                  <div><strong>Joint federal tax returns</strong> — Filing together as "married filing jointly" is the single most powerful document in the I-751 package. Submit the most recent 1–2 years. Include all schedules and W-2s.</div>
                </div>
                <div class="ev-row">
                  <div class="ev-check">&#10003;</div>
                  <div><strong>Joint bank account statements</strong> — 12+ months of statements for a joint account in both names. Shared deposits and shared expenses tell a story of a financially merged household.</div>
                </div>
                <div class="ev-row">
                  <div class="ev-check">&#10003;</div>
                  <div><strong>Joint credit card statements</strong> — Both names on the account; shared household expenses show a real joint life.</div>
                </div>
                <div class="ev-row">
                  <div class="ev-check">&#10003;</div>
                  <div><strong>Named as life insurance beneficiary</strong> — Each spouse listed as primary beneficiary on the other's life insurance policy. This is considered strong because it shows genuine commitment.</div>
                </div>
                <div class="ev-row">
                  <div class="ev-check">&#10003;</div>
                  <div><strong>Retirement or pension beneficiary designation</strong> — Naming each other as beneficiaries on 401(k), IRA, or pension accounts.</div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="ev-cat ev-cat-top">
              <div class="ev-cat-header">
                <div class="ev-cat-icon">&#127968;</div>
                <h3>Shared Residence <span class="ev-strength-badge badge-strong">Strongest</span></h3>
              </div>
              <div class="ev-items-list">
                <div class="ev-row">
                  <div class="ev-check">&#10003;</div>
                  <div><strong>Joint lease or mortgage</strong> — Both names on the lease agreement or mortgage statement for the same address. Include all pages and any renewals.</div>
                </div>
                <div class="ev-row">
                  <div class="ev-check">&#10003;</div>
                  <div><strong>Utility bills</strong> — Electric, gas, water, internet — in both names or at least showing the same address for both spouses. Multiple months across the conditional period.</div>
                </div>
                <div class="ev-row">
                  <div class="ev-check">&#10003;</div>
                  <div><strong>Driver's licenses showing same address</strong> — Both spouses' licenses listing the same home address is clean, simple proof of cohabitation.</div>
                </div>
                <div class="ev-row">
                  <div class="ev-check">&#10003;</div>
                  <div><strong>Government correspondence at shared address</strong> — IRS notices, state tax mail, or Social Security correspondence addressed to both spouses at the same address.</div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="ev-cat">
              <div class="ev-cat-header">
                <div class="ev-cat-icon">&#128203;</div>
                <h3>Insurance &amp; Legal Records <span class="ev-strength-badge badge-good">Strong</span></h3>
              </div>
              <div class="ev-items-list">
                <div class="ev-row">
                  <div class="ev-check">&#10003;</div>
                  <div><strong>Health insurance covering both spouses</strong> — Employer health plan showing the other spouse as a dependent, or a joint health plan enrollment.</div>
                </div>
                <div class="ev-row">
                  <div class="ev-check">&#10003;</div>
                  <div><strong>Joint auto or home insurance policy</strong> — Both spouses listed as insured on the same policy.</div>
                </div>
                <div class="ev-row">
                  <div class="ev-check">&#10003;</div>
                  <div><strong>Joint vehicle title or registration</strong> — Vehicle registered in both names or showing the same address for both spouses.</div>
                </div>
                <div class="ev-row">
                  <div class="ev-check">&#10003;</div>
                  <div><strong>Wills or estate planning documents</strong> — Each spouse designated as heir in the other's will. Shows genuine long-term commitment.</div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="ev-cat">
              <div class="ev-cat-header">
                <div class="ev-cat-icon">&#128106;</div>
                <h3>Children &amp; Family <span class="ev-strength-badge badge-good">Strong</span></h3>
              </div>
              <div class="ev-items-list">
                <div class="ev-row">
                  <div class="ev-check">&#10003;</div>
                  <div><strong>Birth certificate of children born during the marriage</strong> — One of the most compelling pieces of evidence possible. Include the birth certificate naming both spouses as parents.</div>
                </div>
                <div class="ev-row">
                  <div class="ev-check">&#10003;</div>
                  <div><strong>Medical records showing pregnancy during conditional period</strong> — Prenatal records, ultrasounds, OB/GYN visit records — strong evidence of a genuine marital relationship.</div>
                </div>
                <div class="ev-row">
                  <div class="ev-check">&#10003;</div>
                  <div><strong>Children's school or childcare records</strong> — Emergency contact forms, school enrollment forms listing both spouses as parents at the same address.</div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="ev-cat">
              <div class="ev-cat-header">
                <div class="ev-cat-icon">&#128247;</div>
                <h3>Relationship Documentation <span class="ev-strength-badge badge-helpful">Good Supporting Evidence</span></h3>
              </div>
              <div class="ev-items-list">
                <div class="ev-row">
                  <div class="ev-check">&#10003;</div>
                  <div><strong>Photographs spanning the conditional period</strong> — 20–30 photos from different dates, occasions, and settings: holidays, family events, travel, everyday life. Add captions with dates and locations. Do not submit only professional portrait photos.</div>
                </div>
                <div class="ev-row">
                  <div class="ev-check">&#10003;</div>
                  <div><strong>Affidavit letters from people who know the couple</strong> — 2–4 letters from family members or friends who have witnessed the couple living together as a married couple. Letters should be specific, detailed, and include the writer's contact information and relationship to the couple.</div>
                </div>
                <div class="ev-row">
                  <div class="ev-check">&#10003;</div>
                  <div><strong>Joint travel records</strong> — Flight confirmations, hotel bookings, or itineraries showing the couple traveled together during the conditional period.</div>
                </div>
                <div class="ev-row">
                  <div class="ev-check">&#10003;</div>
                  <div><strong>Social media or communication records</strong> — Screenshots of shared social media profiles, tagged photos together, or other digital evidence can supplement primary documents. Not a replacement for financial and residential evidence.</div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="alert-box alert-teal">
            <div class="alert-icon">&#128202;</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Evidence tip: Span the entire conditional period</strong>
              <p>USCIS looks for documents that cover the full 2-year conditional period — not just the most recent months. A joint tax return from Year 1 + bank statements from throughout + your current lease paints a continuous picture. Only submitting very recent documents can raise questions about what was happening earlier in the conditional period.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Mid-page CTA -->
        <div class="cta-mid">
          <h3>Not sure your I-751 package is strong enough?</h3>
          <p>An immigration attorney can review your evidence, identify gaps, and help you build the most persuasive possible petition before you file. A denial is far more costly than a consultation.</p>
