        <!-- Processing times -->
        <section id="processing" class="content-section">
          <h2>I-751 Processing Times in 2026</h2>
          <p>USCIS is currently processing Form I-751 in approximately <strong>24–36 months</strong> at most service centers as of 2026. The backlog has grown significantly since 2020 and shows no sign of rapid resolution. Here's what each stage typically looks like:</p>

          <table class="info-table">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Stage</th>
                <th>Typical Wait</th>
                <th>What You Receive / What to Do</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Receipt notice (I-797)</strong></td>
                <td>2–6 weeks after filing</td>
                <td>Automatic 24-month extension of conditional card. Keep this notice with your green card at all times.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Biometrics appointment</strong></td>
                <td>1–4 months after receipt</td>
                <td>Scheduled at local USCIS Application Support Center (ASC). Bring I-797 and valid ID. Fingerprints, photo, signature taken.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Request for Evidence (RFE)</strong></td>
                <td>Varies — not all cases</td>
                <td>If USCIS needs more documentation, you'll receive an RFE with an 87-day response window. Respond completely — partial responses weaken your case.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Interview notice (if required)</strong></td>
                <td>12–30 months after filing</td>
                <td>Not all cases require an interview. Strong joint petitions are often approved without one. Waiver cases more commonly require interviews.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Approval notice</strong></td>
                <td>24–36 months after filing</td>
                <td>I-751 is approved. USCIS begins producing your 10-year green card.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>10-year green card production &amp; mailing</strong></td>
                <td>2–4 weeks after approval</td>
                <td>New IR-1 or IF-6 green card mailed to your address on file. File Form AR-11 any time you move to keep your address current.</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>

          <div class="alert-box alert-teal">
            <div class="alert-icon">&#128260;</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Processing time exceeds the 24-month automatic extension?</strong>
              <p>Given the current I-751 backlog, many cases take longer than the initial 24-month automatic extension. USCIS has been issuing updated extension notices covering the additional processing time. Watch for mailings from USCIS during this period. If you believe your extension has lapsed and you haven't heard from USCIS, contact them through the online case status tool or by calling 1-800-375-5283.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3>How to check your I-751 case status</h3>
          <p>Use the USCIS online case status tool at uscis.gov/casestatus with the receipt number from your I-797 notice. The receipt number begins with letters (e.g., MSC, IOE, NBC) followed by 10 digits. Updates are not always timely, but major status changes (biometrics scheduled, interview scheduled, approved) do appear there.</p>
        </section>

        <!-- Path to citizenship -->
        <section id="citizenship" class="content-section">
          <h2>From Conditional Green Card to U.S. Citizenship</h2>
          <p>For many international couples, the conditional green card is not the destination — it is a step on the road to U.S. citizenship. Here is the full arc, from your conditional card to naturalization:</p>

          <div class="path-steps">
            <div class="path-item">
              <div class="path-circle path-done">&#10003;</div>
              <div>
                <strong>Step 1 — Conditional green card issued (CR-1 or CR-6)</strong>
                <p>You are now a Lawful Permanent Resident with a 2-year conditional card. Full work and travel rights. The 2-year clock on your I-751 window begins from the card's issue date.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="path-connector"></div>
            <div class="path-item">
              <div class="path-circle path-active">2</div>
              <div>
                <strong>Step 2 — File Form I-751 (months 21–24)</strong>
                <p>Gather evidence of your genuine marriage. File I-751 with your spouse (joint petition) or alone on a waiver basis. Receive I-797 receipt notice with 24-month automatic extension. Continue living and working normally while case is pending.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="path-connector"></div>
            <div class="path-item">
              <div class="path-circle path-pending">3</div>
              <div>
                <strong>Step 3 — I-751 approved → 10-year permanent green card (IR-1)</strong>
                <p>Conditions are removed. You receive your full 10-year Permanent Resident Card with no further conditions. Renew this card every 10 years if you have not naturalized.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="path-connector"></div>
            <div class="path-item">
              <div class="path-circle path-future">4</div>
              <div>
                <strong>Step 4 — Eligible for naturalization after 3 years (if still married to U.S. citizen)</strong>
                <p>Spouses of U.S. citizens get the accelerated 3-year naturalization path — not the standard 5 years. The 3-year clock begins from the date you were first admitted as a conditional permanent resident (not from when I-751 was approved). You must have been married to and living with your U.S. citizen spouse for all 3 years. File Form N-400 90 days before your 3-year anniversary to begin the process.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="path-connector"></div>
            <div class="path-item">
              <div class="path-circle path-future">&#127482;&#127480;</div>
              <div>
                <strong>Step 5 — Naturalization interview, civics test, and oath ceremony</strong>
                <p>Pass the N-400 interview and English/civics test. Attend the oath ceremony. You are now a U.S. citizen. Your <SmartLink href="/affidavit-of-support">I-864 Affidavit of Support</SmartLink> obligation ends at citizenship. You can vote, hold a U.S. passport, and pass citizenship to your children.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="alert-box alert-teal">
            <div class="alert-icon">&#128197;</div>
            <div>
              <strong>The 3-year clock started when you got your green card — not when I-751 is approved</strong>
              <p>Many people assume the 3-year naturalization clock starts over when they get their 10-year card. It does not. The 3-year period counts from the date you were first admitted as a conditional permanent resident — typically the date printed on your original 2-year green card or, for AOS cases, the date USCIS approved your I-485. This means naturalization eligibility and I-751 completion often overlap closely.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- FAQ -->
        <section id="faq" class="content-section">
          <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
          <div class="faq-list">
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>What is a conditional green card?</summary>
              <p>A conditional green card is a 2-year Permanent Resident Card issued when a foreign national receives a marriage-based green card and the marriage is less than 2 years old at the time of approval. It grants the same rights as a regular green card — including work authorization, travel, and re-entry — but expires after 2 years and requires filing Form I-751 to remove the conditions and receive a permanent 10-year card. The card shows a category code of CR-1 or CR-6.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>Who gets a conditional green card vs. a 10-year green card?</summary>
              <p>USCIS determines which card to issue based on how long the couple has been married at the time of approval — not when the petition was filed. If the marriage is less than 2 years old at approval, the foreign spouse receives a conditional (CR-1 or CR-6) 2-year card and must file I-751. If the marriage is 2 years or older at approval, the foreign spouse receives a permanent (IR-1) 10-year card with no I-751 required. Both the CR-1 (spousal visa) and K-1+AOS paths can result in either type of card depending on the marriage duration at approval.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>When do I file Form I-751 to remove conditions?</summary>
              <p>You must file Form I-751 during the 90-day window immediately before your conditional green card expires — between 21 and 24 months after the card's issue date. The easiest way to calculate: look at your card's expiration date and count back 90 days. That is the first day you can file. The card's expiration date is the last day. If you file before month 21, USCIS rejects it and returns your fee. If you file after month 24, you must include a written explanation with good cause for the late filing.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>What happens if I miss the I-751 filing window?</summary>
              <p>File immediately. Do not wait longer than you already have. Include a written explanation with good cause for why you missed the window — illness, family emergency, or other circumstances outside your control. USCIS has discretion to accept late filings. However, once your conditional green card has expired without a pending I-751, you technically have no lawful immigration status in the U.S., and USCIS can initiate removal proceedings. Consulting an immigration attorney is strongly recommended if you have missed the window.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>Can I work and travel internationally with a conditional green card?</summary>
              <p>Yes to both. A conditional green card is a real Permanent Resident Card — it authorizes you to work anywhere in the U.S. without employer sponsorship, and to travel internationally and re-enter the U.S. as a returning resident. After you file I-751, your I-797 receipt notice extends your status and, combined with your expired conditional green card, serves as a travel document for re-entry. Bring both documents every time you travel while I-751 is pending.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>How long does it take to get a permanent 10-year green card after filing I-751?</summary>
              <p>As of 2026, USCIS processes Form I-751 in approximately 24–36 months at most service centers. Upon filing, you receive an automatic 24-month extension of your conditional green card. USCIS has been issuing additional extension notices for cases pending beyond the initial extension period. You can live, work, and travel legally throughout the entire processing period. The total time from your conditional green card being issued to receiving the 10-year card is typically 3–5 years.</p>
            </details>
          </div>
        </section>

